## Building Whack-a-Mole in React

**Mental model:** Two timers drive the game: one *spawn* interval that moves the mole to a random hole, and one *countdown* that ends the round. State is the active hole, the score, the time left, and whether you're playing. Whacking the active hole scores and (optionally) hides the mole. Always clear both timers on cleanup.

### Step 1 — Game state
```jsx
const [active, setActive] = useState(-1);
const [score, setScore] = useState(0);
const [time, setTime] = useState(20);
const [playing, setPlaying] = useState(false);
```

### Step 2 — Spawn the mole on an interval
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  if (!playing) return;
  const id = setInterval(() => setActive(Math.floor(Math.random() * HOLES)), 700);
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, [playing]);
```

### Step 3 — Countdown that ends the game
```jsx
useEffect(() => {
  if (!playing) return;
  const id = setInterval(() => setTime((t) => (t <= 1 ? (setPlaying(false), 0) : t - 1)), 1000);
  return () => clearInterval(id);
}, [playing]);
```

### Step 4 — Whack handler
```jsx
const whack = (i) => { if (playing && i === active) { setScore((s) => s + 1); setActive(-1); } };
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Click empty hole | Only the active hole scores. |
| Timer leak | Both effects return `clearInterval`. |
| Restart | Reset score/time, set `playing` true. |

**Interview tip:** Two independent intervals (spawn + countdown), each with its own effect and cleanup, is the clean decomposition — co-mingling them in one timer is where bugs and leaks creep in.

