## Building Whack-a-Mole in Angular

**Mental model:** Two timers: a *spawn* interval that relocates the mole and a *countdown* that ends the round. Fields hold the active hole, score, time, and playing flag. Whacking the active hole scores. Clear both intervals in `stop()` and `ngOnDestroy`. Classic `NgModule` setup, no `?.`/`??` (the build rejects them).

### Step 1 — Fields
```typescript
active = -1; score = 0; time = 20; playing = false;
private spawnId: any = null;
private tickId: any = null;
```

### Step 2 — Start both intervals
```typescript
start(): void {
  this.score = 0; this.time = 20; this.playing = true;
  this.spawnId = setInterval(() => { this.active = Math.floor(Math.random() * this.HOLES); }, 700);
  this.tickId = setInterval(() => this.tick(), 1000);
}
```

### Step 3 — Countdown
```typescript
tick(): void { this.time--; if (this.time <= 0) { this.time = 0; this.stop(); } }
stop(): void { this.playing = false; this.active = -1; clearInterval(this.spawnId); clearInterval(this.tickId); }
```

### Step 4 — Whack + destroy cleanup
```typescript
whack(i: number): void { if (this.playing && i === this.active) { this.score++; this.active = -1; } }
ngOnDestroy(): void { this.stop(); }
```

**Edge cases**

| Case | Handling |
| :-- | :-- |
| Click empty hole | Only active hole scores. |
| Timer leak | `stop()` clears both; `ngOnDestroy` calls it. |
| Restart | Reset score/time first. |

**Interview tip:** Centralizing both `clearInterval` calls in one `stop()` (also invoked from `ngOnDestroy`) is the clean way to guarantee no orphaned timers when the component leaves the DOM.

